179. Difficiles primum terrm] The same soil does not agree with olives in all countries. Thus Pliny tells us, that a fat soil suits them in some places, and a gravelly soil in others: ‘⁴ Glareosum oleis solum aptissimum ⁶⁴ in Venafrano, pinguissimum in Boe- “ tica.'’ The soil where Virgil lived is ‹lamp, being subject to the inun- dations of the Po, and therefore he recommends the hilly and stony lands for the culture of olives, We find

in Pliny, that the country about La- rissa formerly abounded with olives, but that the land being chilled by the overflowing of a lake they were all lost: “ In Thessalia circa Laris- “ sam emisso lacu frigidior facta ea. “ regio est, oleaque desierunt quae “ prius fuerant.''
